chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Government should set a universal health “floor” that guarantees access to essential care—primary, preventive, mental-health, and emergency services—and strong protection from catastrophic medical bills, while allowing people to choose among competing public, nonprofit, and private plans. The public role should focus on clear minimum standards, income-based help, and enforcing price transparency and fair competition so costs come down without sacrificing quality or innovation. Delivery should lean on local clinics and caregivers, with simple, portable coverage and measurable outcomes to keep the system accountable and fiscally sustainable.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Government should guarantee a clear, affordable baseline of high-quality care—especially primary, preventive, mental-health, emergency, and catastrophic coverage—so no one faces medical bankruptcy and every community has dependable access. That public foundation should be fiscally disciplined and accountable, using price transparency, targeted cost controls, streamlined administration, and measurable outcomes. Within that baseline, policymakers should preserve meaningful patient choice and room for regulated private, nonprofit, and faith- and community-based providers, with special support for rural clinics, caregivers, and portable coverage for workers with changing jobs.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Government should ensure every resident has access to an affordable, dependable baseline of care—primary, preventive, mental-health, and emergency/catastrophic coverage—so no one is bankrupted by illness and seniors, children, and working families can stay healthy. This guarantee should be delivered through simple, accountable programs with strong anti-fraud measures, price transparency, and practical cost controls that reward prevention and better outcomes. People who want additional coverage should be able to choose regulated private options, while public funding and partnerships with local, rural, tribal, and faith- and community-based providers help care reach every community and protect privacy.
